{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3234732,"name":"Alex Tsekhansky","username":"atsekhan","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/0ea827/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-09-24T21:10:39.900Z","cooked":"<p>We’re experimenting with the Linelight (2+ in our case) and Google Coral.</p>
<p>We uploaded the model that the Limelight provided, and everything is working fine. We can make the robot to follow a cone or a cube from any orientation etc.</p>
<p>The question I have is this - in Network Tables the Limelight provides only the Closest target. However, it definitely can see properly multiple ones. Is there a way to get coordinates and types of ALL of the targets it sees, not just the biggest one?</p>
<p>In PhotonVision you could do so via API, but not network tables (for other target types). Does the Limelight API allow you to get ALL of the targets it sees?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2023-09-24T21:10:39.900Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":136,"reads":220,"readers_count":219,"score":724.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":441389,"topic_slug":"limelight-with-google-coral-multiple-gamepiece-targets","display_username":"Alex Tsekhansky","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":50762,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/limelight-with-google-coral-multiple-gamepiece-targets/441389/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3234739,"name":"Jonah Bonner","username":"jonahb55","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jonahb55/{size}/194474_2.png","created_at":"2023-09-24T21:59:22.522Z","cooked":"<p>You’ll want to look at the documentation for the Limelight’s <a href="https://docs.limelightvision.io/en/latest/json_dump.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">JSON interface</a>. They provide a library that can decode it and give you a list of all detections.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2023-09-24T21:59:22.522Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_cou